ce:section.ce:para:
The primary species involved in NO oxidation were identified by the following scavenger tests. Potassium dichromate (K2Cr2O7), potassium iodide (KI), p-benzoquinone(PBQ), and tert-butyl alcohol (TBA) [37] were used as scavengers for electrons (e−
                        ), holes (h+
                        ), superoxide radicals (

                              ·

                                 O
                                 2
                                 -


                        ), and hydroxyl radicals (

                              ·
                              O
                              H

                        ), respectively. The corresponding active species generated by the light excitation of catalyst are trapped and exhausted by the scavengers. An active species plays an important role in photocatalysis if a catalyst loses performance after its scavenger is added. In a typical test, 1.6 mmol of sacrificial agent and 80 mg of catalyst were first dispersed in 10 ml of water,and ultrasonicated for 5 min to achieve uniform dispersion. Then the prepared catalysts were coated onto the glass slide, following the same procedure as introduced above, and dried at 60 °C for 5 h. The glass slide loaded with catalysts was later used for active species scavenger test.
